metadata.name: bonyād #14
metadata.description:
As I grew up, the mesmerizing paintings of Iranian artist Jalal Shabahangi that adorned our walls sparked a desire within me to venture beyond admiration. Inspired, I embarked on a creative journey, aiming to forge a fresh perspective. Through my project, I aimed to reimagine nature using simple shapes – rectangles, circles, and triangles. These foundational forms breathed life into landscapes, while also giving birth to monoliths within the collection. These towering structures became a bridge, uniting the essence of nature with the sleek lines of modernity. Through this union of forms, I aimed to highlight the captivating interplay between contrasting worlds, showcasing the intriguing harmony that emerges from their coexistence.


Please press ‘2’ to ‘7’ to change the resolution (max 5600 × 7000 px).
Use the key ‘S’ to save the output as a PNG file.

metadata.name: Mines #51
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: Mosaic #387
metadata.description:
---
Notes:
- Click to pause/unpause
- The aspect ratio is fixed 1:1 because of the way the grid and movements are generated to make sure they're the same on all screens. 
---
Description:
An 80X80 grid of tiles are scrambled, shuffled, shifted, streamed, transported,
conveyed, moved, deposited. 

There are 15 initial tile states and 5 color palettes. A set of 12 unique motion patterns
are generated for each piece. 
---
Acknowledgements:
This piece is inspired by Kim Asendorf, whose pixel-level algorithms I'm
transfixed by, and Ksawery Komputery, whose algorithmic tile-works I'm crazy
about. 
---
Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5.js 
December 2021, Germany

metadata.name: Ceremony #280
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I’m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. 🥂

Definitely check out “Forever” mode by tapping “F” or mouse click/tap — it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will “never forget” and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that’s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses “…Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.” Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : “Forever” mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start “Forever” mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in “Forever” mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending “&density=2” (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: saprophyte #243
metadata.description:
saprophyte is a real-time interactive particle system based on the principles of stigmergy. 60,000  particles move around the canvas leaving trails behind them as they move, while each particle decides how to move based on the trails left by other particles around it. You can click to erase the trails in an area, forcing the particles to rebuild their structures anew.

Press "c" to capture an image. By default this will save an image at the resolution of the browser window. If you'd like to save an image at a different resolution, you can press "o" to override the browser's resolution and force the piece to render at a resolution of your choice, and then press "c" to capture the image at your chosen resolution. For best results, wait several seconds after changing the resolution to capture an image, as the piece may need time to adjust to the new resolution.

metadata.name: ecologías - A #1755
metadata.description:
ecologías - A

lines are a metaphor for the communication all species engage in. We as humans have a need to leave traces - stories - that others can read and learn from. What will be the traces machines want to leave? This piece employs sinusoidal signals drawn with lines as a simple metaphor for every trace and every language, for every message and every communication.

ecologías-A is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecologías B and ecologías C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro
CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

Built on p5.js, glsl

append &pd=N (N a number) to the URL in live view to increase/decrease resolution
press s to save current image in current resolution
press z,x,g,b,n followed by +/- to increase/decrease, respectively, brightness, contrast, gamma, blur, noise

metadata.name: Brosser #172
metadata.description:
Exploring generative brush strokes to simulate real life paintings. 

- A selection of 19 different palettes
- 4 different drawing styles
- Randomized "color swap" between the primary and secondary colors in each palette

Several other factors determine the output of a piece, including angles, depth, brush length, and brush weight, among others.

metadata.name: 5-grid Compression #83
metadata.description:
The "5-Grid Compression" project is part of the fxhash and RefractionDAO live minting experience at the Tezos South Beach Miami exhibition on December 6th, 2023.

///\\\///\\\///

"5-Grid Compression" is an artistic exploration of self-doubt and self-criticism, reflecting on discarded initial concepts, imperfect prototypes, and unfulfilled aspirations in the realm of art. 
It features five recursive grids, intentionally "compressed" to represent discarded projects as if thrown into a wastebasket. Embracing a raw and unpolished aesthetic, these grids symbolize the often overlooked aspects of the creative process, underscoring the belief that creativity requires time, deep introspection, and persistent exploration. 
This work emphasizes that every incomplete piece or unrealized idea is valuable, offers insight, and is an essential step in the evolution of digital artistry.

///\\\///\\\///

2023, Created with p5.js and chroma.js
